Taiwan Stocks: Asustek, Catcher Tech, Formosa Petrochemical, WPG

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-08-01T05:58:53Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-01/formosa-petrochemical-htc-mediatek-taiwanese-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in  Taiwan  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 1:30 p.m. close in Taipei.  The Taiex Index rose 57.20, or 0.7 percent, to 8,701.38.  Asustek Computer Inc. (2357)  (2357 TT) surged by the 6.9 percent
daily limit to NT$248, after Macquarie Group Ltd. said in a note
third-quarter notebook shipments growth will be 15 percent
higher than the previous three months and second-quarter
operating margin will be higher than estimated. China Times also
reported the new version of its tablet computer “Transformer”
will begin selling in October.  Chief Financial Officer  David Chang  said in Taipei by
telephone the new version of the Transformer will be sold
“around that time,” without giving further details and
declining to comment on the financials of the company.  Catcher Technology Co. (2474 TT) jumped 6.9 percent to a
record NT$269.50, leading Apple suppliers’ shares higher after
Apple Inc. surpassed Nokia Oyj as the world’s biggest smartphone
maker. Foxconn Technology Co. (2354 TT) climbed 6.8 percent to
NT$142. Largan Precision Co. (3008 TT) advanced 2.9 percent to
NT$998.  Formosa Petrochemical Corp. (6505)  (6505 TT), Taiwan’s only
publicly traded oil refiner, slumped 6.9 percent to NT$101.
Chairman Wang Wen-chao and President Su Chi-yi offered to quit
after a fire broke out at a plant early on July 30, the company
said in statements to the stock exchange.  Affiliates  Formosa Plastics Corp. (1301)  (1301 TT) tumbled 6.9
percent to NT$101 and  Nan Ya Plastics Corp. (1303)  (1303 TT) dropped
6.9 percent to NT$74.20. Rival  China Petrochemical Development
Corp. (1314)  (1314 TT) soared 6.9 percent to NT$47.90.  WPG Holdings Ltd. (3702)  (3702 TT), a distributor of electronic
components, increased 6.9 percent to NT$51.50, the biggest
advance since May 24, 2010, after reporting higher-than-
estimated second-quarter net income. The company posted profit
of NT$1.5 billion, higher than the median estimate of NT$1.4
billion by seven analysts in a poll conducted by Bloomberg.  To contact the reporter on this story:
